ones are introduced as means of differentiating otherwise identically pronounced morphemes. However, they do not entirely prevent pronunciation-meaning conflicts from happening, in which case it is up to the listener to resolve them based on the context of the conversation.  %0a%3c %0a%3c A comment on the last part: The occasional occurrence of such conflicts can be a rich source of tone twisters in Mandarin that involves tricky variations of tones, which is not common in English. E.g., "sì shì sì, shí shì shí, shí sì shì shí sì, sì shí shì sì shí“ (four is four, ten is ten, fourteen is fourteen, forty is forty)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Reference:%0a%3c 1. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tone_(linguistics)#Phonation%0a%3c 2. Stanford Phonology Archive. 2019. Mandarin Chinese sound inventory (SPA).%0a%3c In: Moran, Steven & McCloy, Daniel (eds.)%0a%3c PHOIBLE 2.0.%0a%3c Jena: Max Planck Institute for the Science of Human History.%0a%3c (Available online at http://phoible.org/inventories/view/16, Accessed on 2022-09-18.)%0a%3c 3. Ian Maddieson. 2013. Tone.%0a%3c In: Dryer, Matthew S. & Haspelmath, Martin (eds.)%0a%3c The World Atlas of Language Structures Online.%0a%3c Leipzig: Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology.%0a%3c (Available online at http://wals.info/chapter/13, Accessed on 2022-09-18.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0